Eskom CEO Brian Molefe announced his resignation on Friday. He'll officially step down on 1 January. JOHANNESBURG - As the Democratic Alliance (DA) prepares to lay charges against Eskom CEO Brian Molefe this week, the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) is calling for the utility's board to be dissolved.Molefe announced his resignation on Friday. He'll officially step down on 1 January.He's been implicated in state capture claims, but insists his resignation is not an admission of guilt.The DA s Natasha Mazzone says Molefe s resignation is suspicious. We do think it s highly suspicious, as this resignation comes after the Democratic Alliance asked for a meeting where Mr Molefe will be required to testify under oath. The EFF s Mbuyiseni Ndlozi says the entire Eskom board must also go. We call on the Eskom board to also follow the example of Brian Molefe. The EFF will make sure that Parliament disbands them. WATCH: Brian Molefe on the GuptasMolefe features extensively in the Public Protector s State of Capture report, which was released last month, and his close relationship with the Guptas emerged as one of the big outcomes of the investigation.The report found that Eskom helped the Guptas put the Optimum Coal mine out of business and Molefe was in regular contact with the family.In an interview with the Public Protector, Ajay Gupta confirmed that he is very good friends with Molefe.The report found the board of Eskom was improperly appointed. It also found that certain conflicts arose but the Minister of Public Enterprises, Lynne Brown, took no action to prevent them.The report showed cellphone records with diagrams on the numerous times Molefe visited the Guptas in Saxonwold.Between 2 August 2015 and 22 March 2016, Molefe called Ajay Gupta 44 times and Gupta called Molefe 14 times.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)